[1
Date: Tue, 23 Dec 1997 13:33:50 -0600
From: James McKean <x2mckean@exnet.iastate.edu>

I read with interest the description of the mishandling of the hams used in
the church supper that resulted in a major _Salmonella_ outbreak. I was
equally interested in the moderator's parenthetical comment that he/she
would bet a holiday meal that mistakes were also made in the packing house
and on the farm.
It could make an interesting dialogue to determine how that bet outcome
would be finally decided, and by inference, whether the farm is the
appropriate location to place the control bacterial contamination of foods.
What categories of mistakes could the production unit and processor have
made to cause this illness episode?
Why should livestock producers be held as accountable (mod. inference) as
those who obviously abused the process? The information that 6-8% of swine
are salmonella positive (USDA reference) at slaughter probably greatly
underestimates the percentage of pigs exposed and recovered from
subclinical _Salmonella_ infections in the grow-finish period. The problem
is that short of microbial examination of these animals, such a
determination could not be made using currently known information. Serology
will indicate prior exposure, but not the current carrier status.
This is a discussion that needs serious attention from a wide range of
disciplines. It is far too facile to state that bacterial contamination of
foodstuffs must originate with mistakes on the farm or production facility.
Without meaningful and scientifically sound discussions about the critical
control points for bacterial contamination of meats, the USA food supply
may be disrupted by inappropriate control measures which do not increase
the food safety levels of the foods we eat.
--
Dr. James McKean, DVM, JD
