[Thanks to Jim McKean for sharpening the discussion. I decided to digest
his comments rather than choking on them, for he does raise some excellent
points and I am grateful to him moving the discussion "down the field". He
correctly points out that farmers did not make any mistakes similar in
scale to that which the cooks made in the Maryland case. As far as we know
(which is not very much), the farms and slaughterhouses that produced the
hams in question did everything "correctly" as per their standard operating
procedures. This covers errors of commission and I am glad Jim has
clarified that aspect.
I am concerned about errors of omission, however. Producers of hams, like
anyone else producing any product, have an obligation to ensure quality.
Programs that include continuous quality improvements have become the
standard and help revive many industries. Such notions are the
underpinnings of an HACCP based approach to food safety. But 6-8%
contamination wouldn't necessarily allow the producers to say "I have
produced a high quality product and you can look elsewhere for food safety
continuos improvements". The acceptable standard is determined by the
market, and large outbreaks with human death as occurred in Maryland can
only have a negative impact on the market for hams. So I did not intend for
previous comments to infer that producers were responsible for the Maryland
outbreak but only that they had a role to play in food safety.
My supposition is that the kind of preparation phase mishandling seen in
Maryland will occur from time to time, people being human and therefore
fallible. If a low probability of contamination product were to leave the
farm and packing house, then the chances of an outbreak would be reduced.
Only when a cascade of mistakes occur on the consumption phase of the food
continuum do lost opportunities for increasing food safety on the
production and processing side of the food continuum have a measurable
impact on public health. My proposition of a holiday dinner wager should
have distinguished and focused on these lost opportunities for food safety
rather than implying there were mistakes made.
What are these lost opportunities for food safety? Unfortunately, as Scott
Hurd mentions, we do not have good population based data which quantitates
the relative importance of each step in the food production and consumption
process. The first comprehensive "farm to table" risk assessment for food
safety is still in the works. Lacking such data and other farm based
studies we cannot recommend specific procedures to effectively reduce
_Salmonella_ levels on swine farms. Furthermore, we have to identify cost
effective solutions or the price of safe food will go up.
Fortunately, with the exception of the Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. birthday
celebration, the next holidays on the calendar demand either fasting or
moon cakes and I do not think even I can get into any trouble with those.
Whoops! I just hit that blinking send button. Can I have it back? Moon
cakes, fasting, food safety, please just save your cards and letters. -
Mod.PC
